“I think she is on the way!”-Mama J, 3 years ago today. 

We were sitting in Sunday School when Mama J sent me a text saying she was going to head over to the hospital soon, she was having contractions. 
We were a 16 hour drive away or a 2 hour flight and 1 hour drive. It was the Sunday after thanksgiving, literally the highest ticket prices of the year. Every penny we had was already in holding with still more to save, but thankfully my mama had airline points we could use.
Within a few hours time we were in the same airport, as the family from home alone, as rushed and as hurried as they ran then too. 
After a little while, it was clear baby girl wasn’t quite ready, but what it gave us was a couple days with Mama J that was the gift the Lord new we all needed. 
We got to enjoy Cracker Barrel and go shopping together. Time I think we all needed to get to know each other, the nerves we all felt shifted to butterflies and excitement as we walked in anticipation together. 
Fitting for the first Sunday of advent, and surely not without a still a few worries and fears. We had waited for so long it was strange to move into a space of hope as we walked an uncharted path.
Our village rallied around us from near and far to insure the safe arrival of the baby and mama we had so long prayed for. 
December 1st, a pivotal day, a rush of emotions, and spiritual reminder that God leaves NO DETAIL out.

A week before Z was born, I was having a difficult time processing a million emotions and began questioning everything.

>What if we still don’t have enough money?
>What if she changes her mind?
>What if there is a fluke with paperwork?
>What if I don’t get all my work done in time?
>What if I’m not ready or equip to be a mom?
>What if the baby doesn’t “attach” to me?
>Am I treating Momma J with love, kindness and grace? Have we been supportive or ever crossed the line to coercion?
>Will Justin get enough time with her before he leaves?
😞

>>>I could go on and and on. My mind sure did. I wish i could say it stopped when she was born, or when we signed papers, or when we brought her home. However, it didn’t happen suddenly even if it looked like it from the outside.

I was physically holding the promise that just a few days before seemed so close yet so far away. From the outside the shift and the promise looks sudden, but I argue it’s rarely suddenly delivered.

God slowly peeled back the layers of fear and disbelief and poured in joy and hope. It didn’t happen passively, our worship became our weapon. We pleaded and petitioned, we prayed and praised our way through those days, but it didn’t start just a week before she was born.
 It began 12 years ago when i promised Justin’s momma i would take care of him and have “pretty babies”. It continued 8 years ago when I had surgery and the doctors said I might not ever be able to have children and then again when we applied to begin the adoption process 3 years ago. It all culminated over those last few weeks in anticipation and praise as our girl made her way.
✨
Promises may look like they were delivered in an instance, especially from the outside looking in. However, they are the revelation and unveiling of faith through God’s grace. 
Today, I hope you know that even though you might be in a bleak place, please know and YOU BETTER BELIEVE that God is working all things together.
Please, don’t forget that the glue that holds your flesh together on the hard days, the real hard days, is the prayer and the praise you give God through your worship while you wait.

Why do we do it? 
By “we,” I mean parents as a collective.
Why do we go all out for Christmas? 
Why do we save and sacrifice for gifts?
Why do we lose sleep, stress over finding the EXACT item?
Why do we wake up early to turn on music, the twinkly lights, and bite a cookie?
✨
We do it because it’s what love does. 
Love is listening to those tiny request and checking the list, then orchestrating a ruckus to make them come true. 
Love is going without, someone you value can behold. 
Love is the magic creates a glimmer of excitement in a dark and cold winter.
Love comes down a chimney and makes “foot prints of snow,” but it’s because we were taught how love and parent my man who came down earth.
He didn’t have to. We don’t have to. 
But His love for us is extravagant, it is the tiny details of year our prayers. It is in wild orchestration of divine moments that make our life worth living. 
It’s not about the dollar amount spent or number of gifts that counts. It’s in the tiny moments of belief and anticipation as we emulate the magic of the first Christmas by encouraging the wonder and fulfilling promises of joy.
I pray your Christmas is filled with joy, laughter and peace in knowing you have a Heavenly Father will give you far more than you could ask or imagine, if you choose to believe. ❤️ Merry Christmas.❤️

“Is he she yours?” - A random lady questioned me. She wasn’t being inquisitive, she was making a statement. Her tone and body language weren’t out of sincerity, she was passing judgement.
▫️
I froze. It stung. I could feel the heat rise in me. I quickly responded with a nice, “She is,” and a snarky smile. The kind you give to the mean girl from high school when you run into her years later at the grocery store.
🙃
The kind of smile that says you suck, screw you, didn’t your mom raise you better? Masked with sugar coated southern belle grin.
👊🏻
I wanted to punch her. The heat hit my fingers as my blood boiled and I swear I could have zapped her with a fire ball. She unknowingly cast her stone right into deep wound.
▫️
She gave me the polite head nod and returned a snarky smile, and we continued on our way.
▫️
I knew it would happen. I knew it would suck. I knew it would sting. I just didn’t know it would be today.
▫️
As an adoptive momma it is common and normal to struggle for weeks with feeling like your baby is REALLY your child. I didn’t get 9 months to bond and get use to the idea of being her momma, and though I loved her more than anything at first sight, for a couple weeks it felt a lot like long term baby sitting. Our bond has taken time, but the roots are growing strong and deep.
✌🏼✌🏾
We don’t match and she will never hear “you look just like your Momma.” We don’t have the same skin color or DNA, but she IS mine. She, is my best girl and I am her momma.
❤️

3 Things I’m Doing to Get Out of a Funk
1) MEDITATE : Spending intentional time in prayer and reflection to start my day. 15 minutes of recentering my spirit can change the trajectory of my whole day.
✨
2) HYDRATE: “Liquids till lunch.” I have gotten back to intermittent fasting, and working on regulating my sugar intake. I forget how much blood sugar spikes can effects energy levels and mood swings, which are both major components of this funk.
✨
3) CREATE : Doing something everyday that allows me to switch into the right side of my brain and go into creative autopilot. It’s ranged from watercolor painting, decorating a book shelf, playing handbells at church to coloring with Zadie Ann. It’s crazy how much it has helped reset my brain when it feels overwhelmed or stressed.
✨
Today is day 12 and I am feeling so much better than I did two weeks ago. At this point in the process, it’s time to focus on refining my routine and processes to help keep me in a good space. If you find yourself in a funk, I hope this series has helped you feel a little less alone. It has surely encouraged me to know that we are walking out of it together. ❤️

Three months ago today, an innocent, perfect, bright eyed baby girl was placed into my arms.
I get asked, “Did you feel like a mom at first site?” or people will just say, “ I bet she felt like she had always been yours.”
✨
But the truth is, neither is true, not because I didn’t love her immediately but because I had grown to love and care for the woman who had been carrying her for the last nine months.
✨
When I watched Mama J bring Zadie Ann into this world and then immediately hand her to me, I saw the true strength of a Mother in her eyes. I was becoming a mother, but in that moment the title of mom, was all hers.
✨
Mama J loved this girl SO MUCH she fought hard to find the right family for her. She pushed back to her counselors when they told her, her standards are too high, and when they gave her a round of profiles, she asked to see more. 

Her relentless love is what made our paths cross, we weren’t even “active” when she first started the search for parents. BUT GOD. 
✨
We were in the second round of profiles and she found what she was looking for in two strangers who wanted to become parents.
😭
It was because of the relentless love of a woman i had never meant and the faithfulness of God, that I would be chosen to become a Mom.
✨
I might not have felt like a Mom right of the bat, but i felt the weight of being chosen. For someone who has never felt like enough being chosen with so much caution and care means everything.
Being chosen to love, raise, and Shepard our girl has been the greatest overwhelming feeling. The belief that Mama J has in us, the trust she Has in God, and strength she carries in her heart is something I pray Zadie Ann carries everyday of her life.

I have never done something that made me so nervous. I walked into the courthouse along side 9 other bidders, all whom were men old enough to be my dad.

I knew their pockets were much deeper than mine, I knew the house to them was investment, and for me it felt like a pipe dream.

I didn’t know whether to cry or throw up. I had spent the last 10 days doing all the research on homes in foreclosure, tried to get in touch with the owners next of kin, reopened my HS bank account, and for the second time in 2 years, drained it. 

The next 12 weeks were an anxious time were our bid would be upset 4 times. Each time on the last day in the last hour. It was exhausting, especially a state away. I flew back and forth trying to do what I could, and just praying each time would be the last time.

Our last bid was an absolute Hail Mary. If we didn’t get it, the house would go to an investor and it pained me just to think of it. 

But as you now know, that Hail Mary was heard and our prayer felt answered as we were able to close on the home we declared in High School would be ours.

She’s an old girl that needed a lot of love, but I am so grateful we were given the chance to bring her back to life.
We weren’t expecting that. 😅

Being a woman is a freakin ROLLERCOASTER each month. I have a whole alphabet of issues attached to my cycle; PMDD, PCOS, ENDO. They play a big role in my overall health, hormones and fertility, but on days like today, they just straight up make me feel useless and miserable.

March is ENDOMETRIOSIS Awareness month, and if you are a women who struggles with intense stomach cramps, back pain, and heavy bleeding during your cycle, then I would highly consider talking to your doctor. For me the pain can lead to dizzy spells, light headedness, migraines and throwing up.

I have had 3 surgeries, internal and external pelvic floor therapies, dry needling, and therapeutic massages to help, but more than anything, I have learned I just have to give myself grace a few days a months. It’s okay to need to rest, it’s okay to need to cancel plans to soak in a bath for relief, or lay in bed with your emotional support heating pads.

Endometriosis is chronic invisible illness that affects 1 in 10 women, and if you are a part of that 10% too, please know you are not alone, but I sure wish you didn’t have to know this pain too.❤️

✨Triggered✨How a single photo put me in the fetal position…
Today I was checking my “memories” on Facebook and shifted the trajectory of the rest of my day. 3 years ago today, I stood alone in the hallway of Vanderbilts Children’s hospital, having just been told my daughter could possibly have brain cancer. 

The photo put me back in the hallway. I could smell the sterile scene, i could hear the click of the medical crib as they took her away, and i could feel every ounce of fear all over again.

I never showed it 3 years ago, but it was like today it all came back and was bubbling over. I started shaking, my breath quickened and I could feel tightening.

I laid down beside Z who was napping sent my code word text to J and mom and pulled the covers over my head. I knew it would get worse before it got better.

They knew what was happening, even without knowing the trigger they knew I needed them.

I’ve never been triggered by this before, but I have learned that part of healing is allowing things to come up that we once buried deep. I had to go into autopilot, I was alone, there was a global health crisis, j was deployed, I didn’t have a choice.

But now in my *healing era* I have been learning to allow my self to feel all the things I once pushed so far down I thought I would never see them again. But I’ve learned I have to do the work.
 
Is it hard? Yes. 
Is it sometimes humiliating to be shaking crying, frozen in fear, and unable to speak? Of course.

It’s taken years to get here. To be in safe enough place to allow the emotions, to be able to notice the trigger, send out an SOS, and work through the panic attack, fight or flight response, and after shocks.

But how can I teach my toddler how to feel and process her emotions if I don’t take time to process my own? 

So tonight, I am extra thankful for a safe season to be able to press into the healing, having people who know my codewords and know how come along side me, and a faith I can cling to when the waves of panic and fear come on too strong.
Shout to all my sisters who are healing, who are working through trauma, and breaking generational curses; darkness has no power over the light you carry.

Today we remember Uncle L.M.
for his ultimate sacrifice.
February 25, 1944 was the last day of the "Big Week" operation, in Regensburg Germany. Lonnie Moore Denning was asked to fill in for another radio man who had become ill. His substitution on this flight was suppose to be his last mission before commissioning as a Lieutenant, but he never made it to his promotion. 

His B-17 was one of 97 shot down only hours before the end of the operation. Uncle L.M. Is buried in Northern France, with thousands of other soldiers.

"L.M." was my Papa's older brother. Papa, a recent basic training graduate, received the news of his death while he himself was preparing to deploy out of Hayes, Kansas. 

Though the Denning family was stricken with grief Papa's younger brother, Jerry, joined the war the following summer. 

I can't imagine the amount of grief, pride, and patriotism my Great Grandparents must have carried. To have three sons in one war is unimaginable.

“What’s wrong? - J asked. “I look like a blubbering whale.” I screeched back.
I saw a picture of myself that was really unflattering and it’s messed me up in the head.
I feel like I look as if I have gained 50lbs and am disgusting. Like a busted can of biscuits stuffed into Lululemon shorts.

It’s stupid. I know it’s not true, atleast not totally. Did i probably gain a few pounds on vacation? Probably and the lack good posture certainly contributes to the unflattering shot. However, though not totally true, the thought sits on my brain like an itchy sweater I can’t get off. Annoying and uncomfortable. Reminding me that I am inconsistent and a failure. Shew, it really can spiral fast.

But it’s really not the 5lbs of daiquiris and ice cream that’s making me feel terrible. It’s the stress of the move manifesting in what seems like a controllable area of my life. 
I can’t control what life will look like in two weeks or plan out where we are moving again next year, but I can “control” how I look.
I’m stressed and envious. Jealous of people who can plan. People who live in a world where planning out your life isn’t based the army’s training calendar and move cycles. I am jealous of people who can family plan and get pregnant right on schedule. I’m jealous of people who can make a plan and stick to it because they don’t have neurodivergent brain that struggles with execution functions and task management.
It feels unfair and I want to throw up my hands and yell “WHAT EVEN IS THE POINT?!
✨
But the point is, it all matters. For whatever reason, it’s the cards I’ve been dealt, not as a curse, but necessary parts of my journey. I don’t have to understand it, but it is important to feel it and acknowledge it. After all, I can’t heal it, if I can’t name it. 
✨
Today, the jumbled up feelings manifested as fat shaming myself, a failed attempt at trying to grasp for control in a chaotic season. So here’s to trying to process these feelings of shame, stress, fear, and jealousy - Reminding myself that what seems to be the problem, is usually only the surface issue and then I’ll bless and release all of this because holding on takes too much energy.

You’ve heard the phrase “life partner” and I think that’s exactly what it is. Someone you tag team with, someone who helps carry the load, and ultimately shares the same vision. I am so grateful to have such a good partner in J. 💕

3am came way to early. As soon as my feet hit grown and I grabbed my bags, the regret was quickly replaced my nerves. 

It was a quiet ride to airport, but the questions that flooded my mind were loudly on loop. “What if she doesnt show up?” “What if she doesnt like me?” “Will she think I am different in person?” 
…
The knot in my stomach made it hard eat full breakfast so I settled for pistachios and and water, the Nun in front of grabbed a chocolate bar, i appreciated the choice of chocolate at 4am. 

When I sat down at my gate, a gentleman in his son sat down beside me. The father asked me where I was traveling to, and I gave him a quick explanation. He quickly interjected that he had 3 adopted sons. I am sure I looked shocked, it instantly felt like a Godwink and the tension dropped from my shoulders. 

I arrived in Chicago for my connection and looked for a coffee shop, I couldn’t fall asleep on the first flight and figured it wouldn’t on the next either, so might as well grab some caffeine. While in line, I saw a second Nun. Weird. I couldn’t tell you the last time I had seen a nun in person, surely it’s been years, and two now in two different states? Weird.

But it was in the third state, my destination, where I brushed shoulders with a third Nun that I accepted what seemed like like a strange occurrence as another sign that God was with me. 

I changed clothes and did my makeup in the bathroom of the airport and Ubered over to the meet up spot. First arrived the counselor, then baby boy’s mama and over the next 6 hours we ate, shopped, and talked all over town. 

We talked about how we were raised, what were important values to us, and even possible names. It was such a sweet time together and as time went on, all the the nerves were replaced with excitement. 

By the time I made it back to the hotel, I was completely overwhelmed with gratitude. I will never get over the honor it is to be asked to raise someone else’s baby. 

Adoption is beautiful and heart breaking all at the same time, regardless of what happens, I hope this boy always knows how much he was loved and advocated for from the very start.

As a military family, “see you laters” are a part of our lifestyle, and I’ll tell you, they haven’t always been easy. When J and I dated long distance in college, we went from being separated by a 4.5 drive and only went a couple weeks apart, too being across the country and months.
Over the last 10 years of this lifestyle, we have learned what works best and I wanted to share a few of our best practices: 
1) Already have your next time together on the calendar before you see say “see you later.”
>The times I have had to leave fly out without knowing when I would see him again were the hardest. Whether it’s two weeks out or 9 months, put something on the BIG on the calendar. But most of the time it’s simply the “knowing” I will see him again that puts my mind at ease.
2) We all get a “pass” for a treat after airport goodbyes.
> There is often tears, so having a pick me up right after the security line helps. When I traveled alone, i would sit down for a good dinner and enjoy a drink and  dessert all to myself. When we were broke the splurge was usually my favorite magazine. Today, i passed my splurge to Z and she got to pick out a toy and a big kid drink (Gatorade), while Justin opted to go home and download a new video game. 
3) Have someone you care about on the otherside of the travel day. Being welcomed back home by people you love and surrounded by people who you can express your emotions around process the shift back to “new normal” is so helpful.
✨
They may seem like silly ideas, but as someone who has had meltdowns in airports across the country, I can assure you that it’s the little things that help the most. We are champs at it now, even though it doesn’t necessarily make it easier, it gives me the confidence to make it through each goodbye.

J and I have been doing LDR off and on since I was 16 years old 😅, when he went off to college 5 hours away. In the 14 years since, we have spent countless months separated and have learned a thing or two that makes it work for us.

1️⃣Clear Communication about expectations. 
Seems obvious, but if you don’t have a direct conversation and check-ins you can quickly get off the same page. Do you like to be in constant texting throughout the day or would you rather have a longer phone check in in the evening? Who is coordinating the details for the next rendezvous together? 

2️⃣Make a routine even while apart. 
Every night before bed, we FaceTime have Z brushes teeth and chat (undistracted) about the day and spend quality time “together.” But maybe your routine is a phone call every morning too or from work. You have to figure out what works for you, but having a consistent time helps reinforce stability and consistency in your relationship.

3️⃣Have your own hobbies/interest that you can spend time doing while you are a part. 
For me, it’s always been crucial to join a group/organization I can volunteer with and put my energy into, that has looked like a sorority, spouse’s club, FRG leader, and local civic organizations. For J, he has a small group of friends he play games with on the weekends.

4️⃣Make your reunification special and intentional.
Before having Z, we would go on little “staycations” or date-days when we got back together. But now, those days have turned into special family outings. It doesn’t have to cost a lot of money, it could be a picnic at the park, but doing something outside of your routine gives you special memories and has always helped us reintegrate into life back together.

5️⃣Give yourself grace. 
It is okay to be sad, feel frustrated, and sometimes even resentful of the situation. Feel the feeling, communicate it if you need to, but then release it. Living in those feelings wont make the time pass any faster (trust me, I know.) Stay busy, get involved, and remember you don’t have to be with your person to love them well.

Friday, was a month since our Lawyer called to let us know baby boy would not be joining our family.
It was a pivotal.Every decision we had made, every prayer we had made, every “it will be worth it when” over the previous 2 months came to a screeching halt and in that moment felt like a door had been shut in our face.
I honestly don’t have another heartache to compare it too. When I miscarried, I didnt even know I had been pregnant and we hadn’t yet started our TTC journey so the grief was much delayed. This was an immediate gut punch, like an unexpected breakup to someone you love, I was proud of Mama for doing what was best for her, but devastated for us.
I balled up in bed and J held me while I repeated, “my heart just hurts,” and affirmed “I know.”
 I worried for Mama, “Does she have what she needs? This was not her plan.” I cried for baby, “Will he know how much he was loved, prayed,and cared for, even before his birth?” “Will he be okay?”
My heart hurt in the most real sense I can explain to you. J packed our bags, I couldn’t manage, and truth be told it’s still packed. From what I remember, J called my mom to let her know that he had booked a ticket home and would be headed to the airport soon.
We had brought a car seat, I now couldn’t bare to look at it. I told him I couldn’t take it home. Even though it had carried our girl home almost 4 years before, it no longer felt like hers or ours.
I told J he could ask them to throw it away or donate it, Idc.
I changed clothes, I needed to shed the layer i had planned to wear to the hospital, and removed my make up. 
I felt broken, I was nauseous, and on the verge of a panic attack, but it felt like God was was telling me we still had something to give. I was angry, but convicted.
I calmed down enough to tell J, we need to leave the car seat for Mama because I was worried how they would get home. So we did. We left it at concierge for our counselor to pick up.
I immediately felt like it might be our last opportunity to prove that we were in this process to support her to the very end, no matter the outcome.
A month later, I can tell you that I have no regrets. Grief is hard, but peace can coexist with heartache.

“Am I good enough to be a mom?” - a question I asked for years going through infertility.
✨
I wasn’t questioning how prepared I was or whether I thought I would be “good at it,” I was confident in both of those things.
Instead, it was a question of morality and faith. I was always the “good girl.” I followed the rules, I never “went wild” or strayed from my faith and I naively thought that meant things like getting pregnant would be simple. M
Was I praying enough? Was I giving enough? Was I pure in heart enough?

Im not sure how you would even begin measure those things, but I thought surely that getting pregnant was something I was suppose to “achieve” and my inability to perform had to be a result of something I was doing wrong.
I prayed. I changed my diet. I tithed more. I had surgery. I tracked my temperature and read scripture.
Nothing I did was “good enough.”
I had tangled my worth with my health and my accomplishments. I had equated my faith to the culmination of righteous acts.
✨
For the first time in my life I couldn’t make something work by shear determination and will. It broke me.
✨
As an achiever, it was a hard realization that my “goodness” would never be enough. I had to surrender all of it.
✨ 
I had to learn how to release and heal instead of trying to prove and earn. 
When we walked into the adoption process in 2019, I was a different woman than the girl who thought having a baby was something owed to be because of my own righteousness. I was worried I again wouldn’t be good enough to be chosen by a stranger to raise her baby. It was a paradigm shift I silently struggled with, so fearful of rejection.
✨
I didn’t deserve the chance to be Zadie Ann’s mom. But when Mama J chose us, it was the first time I had felt enough.  It was humbling then, and even more so now.
I’m so grateful that my journey to motherhood wasn’t something I could earn, I’m not sure I would be able to appreciate it as much.
I just wish I could tell 25 year old me, “it’s not about your goodness, it’s out of their grace.”

Being just days out from a third “failed” placement the realities of adoption feel entirely too fresh. Adoption is complicated to say the least, and over the last 4 years we have learned so much more about what it means to “support adoption.”
We believe in adoption. We couldn’t be more grateful for adoption. However, it doesn’t mean that adoption is always “good.” People use adoption as profitable commodity, that is not “good.” Vulnerable women are coerced into making decisions by people with more power and money, that is not “good.” Babies go home from the hospital without the one person they have depended on for the last 9 months, that is not “good.”
✨
Adoption is complicated. Adoption is complex. Adoption is hard. Adoption it traumatic. Yet, it can be good. It can be wonderful. It can be a blessing and a divine union of families ready for a lifelong journey.
But today, in the midst of a hard season in our adoption journey, to sum it up with a smiley face doesn’t feel authentic in the least. It’s a pretty princess band-aid on a deep wound.
Tonight, I am grateful than ever that we have been able to experience the goodness of adoption. That we have been transformed by the process and that we have a perfect girl because of it. 
But I am also sitting in the friction of waiting for our next “yes” while being so damn proud of the 3 strong women who chose to raise their babies. ❤️

The holiday season can be stressful even when life hasn’t necessarily been “hard,” but if you’re walking through a season of grief or overwhelm, the holidays can feel like salt on a wound.
I’m not here to tell you to grin and bear it, or offer some kind of cheap positive affirmations, but I want to share how I am actively working through this season for myself and maybe a couple ideas that might help you too.
1) Most importantly, managing expectations. I’ve been open and honest with those around me with the feelings of grief and overwhelm. Being transparent about how I’m doing allows room for me to show up in whatever way I can, clues people in to why I might not be showing up in a way they are use too. Maybe for you it can also reinforces boundaries about hosting, traveling, or even gift giving. 
2) Reframing what “Christmas Magic” looks like in my mind. For me, this means letting go of the idea that my home has to be Southern Living worthy in order to create picture memories. It also might look like finding ways to create Christmas cheer without spending a ton of money.
3) Reminding myself that grace is the best gift I can give myself and anyone else. So when things don’t meet expectations, don’t feel magical, or just straight up suck because they may never be what they use to be or we hoped to be. 
In that same notion of grace, I also remember that not every holiday season is going to be perfect or feel like this, and it’s okay if this one isn’t a banner season. 
✨
I hope your holiday feels warm and fuzzy and full of magic, but if it doesn’t that’s okay too. ❤️

I thought I could feel it, a knowing, a seed of hope and belief that this would be the year. Somehow, someway.
There were many days when it felt like a distant dream, but there were also days where I was so confident I bought the most precious Christmas onesie just standing in faith that it would happen.
✨
It’s hard to explain the kind of grief that comes when you have no proof of loss and nothing has been lost but our own hope and expectation.
Whether you are also going through the loss of expectation, exhaustion from “trying,” or years of infertility, please know you have a friend and sister in me. 
I know what it’s like to pack up a suitcase of sweet tiny boy clothes. I have hidden items from myself and turned the nursery into a storage room of all the baby items I can’t bare to look at. 
✨
I know what it’s like for your heart to ache when someone ask when you will “try again,” as you wonder if your heart could take it again.
I know what it’s like to feel with anger when someone says, “at least you didn’t really ‘lose’ your ‘own’ baby.”
I know sister, I know.
I know about the thermometer you keep by the bed, pillow under your hips, and tear stained TTC journal.
✨
I pray your grief, and mine, can be transformed into hope and be reminded that Christmas isn’t just about “knowing” and certainty of a promise.It was set in the midst of chaotic scene that seemed bleak, until it wasn’t. Hope on hold, until it became fulfilled.

So we will holdfast to that hope, may it not be on hold forever.

I keep getting asked why we didn’t move out to Kansas City when the adoption fell through, so we could all be together.
I wish it would have been that cut and dry of a decision. However, when we decided that J would become a “geo bachelor” and I would stay here with Zadie Ann, we knew it wouldn’t be one we would be able to change our mind on.
✨
The apartment in KC is small one bedroom, perfect size for just him and a great location for when we come to visit (we can walk everywhere), which is important when you only have one car. A one bedroom also kept monthly cost lower than a 3bedroom that we would need if we were all there full time.
And when we decided to stay, that also meant Z would get to go back to school and the same place as last year (a rare opportunity for military kids). She also got to start dance at the same studio I danced at for 15 years, a moment I had dreamed of since before she was born. 

In addition to those things, I too replanted myself here at home. I joined my local women’s civic organization, chamber, and accepted the opportunity to serve as a deacon at our church. 
So when we found out that all our plans around baby boy would no longer come to fruition, trying to go back to our original plan also meant going back on so much more. 
Don’t get me wrong, it’s been incredibly difficult, and I haven’t been shy about how many hard days have filled my calendar. But, this isn’t our first time being separated as a family and most likely not our last. (You have to remember I started my solo parenting journey when J deployed when Z was just 5 weeks old.)
✨
Being home has allowed me to be here for moments my family needed me, and when I needed them. Being home has allowed Z a sense of stability and root-planting that bejng an adopted-military kid doesn’t often afford. It’s also given J the chance to study, write, and read for his program without feeling guilty. 
It might not make sense to you, and you might not have made the same decision, but for us, it was right.
Thankfully, we only have a handful of months to go. 😅

One of the things you quickly realize when you become parents is how FEW photos you have of just the “two” of you anymore. 😅 So, when I was recently asked for a professional quality photo of just J and I, I was met with the reality that the last professional photos of just us two were for our last Adoption profile book, 4.5 years ago. 

Last weekend, while J was home I told him we had to snap a quick photo for the interview, but also because I know we will need it for our new adoption profile book too. 

You see, in the fall, we never had to complete a full book as we had before. It’s usually one of the very first steps of the process, but since we jumped in with a quick turnaround and based on referral, we had kind of skipped that step. 

I have known since about mid November, that I needed to make a new book. One of the ways we were able to save money the first go around was by putting my graphic design and photography degrees to good use, and I took weeks to design the perfect book to represent us. 

Mama J, Zadie Ann’s biological mommy was the ONLY mama to ever see it, a true anomaly, as we were prepared to present dozens of times over the course of months.

So this time around, I have felt the weird pressure to be able to design the “perfect” book again. I have put it off, shelved it and archived the folder on my computer for it because my “what if I do it wrong and fail” button has been triggered again and again.

But today, I’ll add these photos to folder and try and remind myself that we weren’t chosen because of my choice of fonts or photos. But because there was connection between who we are and what Mama J was looking for, and I believe that a connection like that is possible again.
